post_text: Beginning Monday, September 14, Big Lake Schools will be offering free meals for all children grades preK-12 each day. Breakfast and lunch will be provided at no cost to all children enrolled in Big Lake Schools. This is feasible due to an extension of the meal service waiver offered through the United States Department of Agriculture (USDA).

"It was very quick and easy to operate, and if I made a mistake it was relatively simple to fix said mistake later" -Big Lake alumni Cole T. sharing his experience with Edgenuity.

Big Lake Online is powered by the platform Edgenuity. Edgenuity is used nationwide by districts for credit recovery, intervention, summer school and supplemental credits. Additionally, Edgenuity is an award winning platform for their advances in the education field. Big Lake High School has used this platform for the past 14 years to provide exceptional learning opportunities to students.

For more information visit our website: https://www.biglakeschools.org/domain/133

post_text:
Question: How are Big Lake Schools preparing for the 2020-21 school year?

Answer: Like other districts in Minnesota, we are following guidance from the Minnesota Department of Education, Minnesota Department of Health, and Centers for Disease Control and Prevention. Schools have been told to plan for three scenarios:

• In-person learning for all students
• Hybrid learning with strict social distance and capacity limits
• Distance learning only

The Minnesota Department of Education has shared that all three scenarios may be used at any time throughout the school year. Throughout the coming weeks, you can expect more information from us on our district plan covering all three scenarios.

Guidance documents provided by the Minnesota Department of Education and Minnesota Department of Health can be found here:

https://content.govdelivery.com/accounts/MNMDE/bulletins/2915c94?reqfrom=share&fbclid=IwAR2iQow5xN0sv_aBBowC90v4sdDUcGFyDxJ2xI9zxk3D0qmwbxpc4uqP8B8

post_text:
At the end of this school year, Big Lake Schools will say goodbye to four longtime teachers who have dedicated more than a combined total of 133 years to educating our students. Deb Campbell has been a teacher for 34 years, 28 of which were in Big Lake.

"I have seen many changes in education over the years, especially in regards to technology. There are so many good memories that I will take with me and think of fondly. I will really miss working with (and the relationships with) the students and staff of Big Lake Schools, and all the friendships that have been established over the years. In retirement, I am looking forward to spending quality time with my husband, family, and friends, and traveling"

Congratulations Ms. Campbell! We will miss you!

post_text:
At the end of this school year, Big Lake Schools will say goodbye to four longtime teachers who have dedicated more than a combined total of 133 years to educating our students. Todd Skinner has been teaching for 33 years.

"I can't believe how quickly time has passed! I've learned that I'd rather be called a teacher than an educator. The latter focuses more on content and standards. I believe that a teacher focuses on the whole child. Relationships matter and some learning can't be measured on a state test. My first class of fourth graders are now 43 years young. I still pictures them as ten-year-olds with bright eyes, smiles, and an ability to appreciate the wonders of the world. I hope all the students I've worked with know I continue to care."

Congratulations Mr. Skinner! We will miss you!

post_text:
At the end of this school year, Big Lake Schools will say goodbye to four longtime teachers who have dedicated more than a combined total of 133 years to educating our students. Claudia Forsberg has been a teacher for 39 years.

"I was hired in 1981 at the old schoolhouse in downtown Big Lake by Principal Rollie Olson- it seems that was only yesterday. He said a new school (Independence) was being built where I'd be teaching 5th grade. I've enjoyed my teaching journey from elementary to middle school and now ending my career at the high school. I'm glad I chose a profession that I loved because it made going to work easy. Now ending my teaching career virtually in the middle of a pandemic seems crazy. I'll miss teaching. I'll miss the students, and I'll miss the other teachers."

Congratulations Ms. Forsberg! We will miss you!

post_text:
At the end of this school year, Big Lake Schools will say goodbye to four longtime teachers who have dedicated more than a combined total of 133 years to educating our students. Mark Boeckman has worked 36 years in education and 33 years at Big Lake.

"I have enjoyed working with all of my colleagues over the years; I will miss the good times and conversations. It has been more than just a job to me. I have formed many lifelong friendships. Making connections with students not only as a teacher, but also as a coach, is something I will never forget. Memorable moments include when Chuck Heitz dressed as MC Hammer and lip synched and dance to Hammer Time during a pep fest, watching John Muir dress up like Roy Orbison and sing Pretty Woman, meeting my wife at a staff meeting, and being able to teach where my boys went to high school."

Congratulations Mr. Boeckman! We will miss you!

Congratulations Mr. Boeckman! We will miss you!

Big Lake Community Education
April 17 at 9:18 AM ·

Online registration for summer programming is open now! Kids Club and Hive Time summer registration is also open. During the registration process, no payment will be taken, but your spot will be reserved by your credit card. Confirmation of your registration will show that your payment will be deducted 1 week before the class starts. Due to the uncertainty of how COVID-19 will affect the future of Community Education programming in our community, we have opted to delay mailing a printed catalog.

When we are ready to accept payment we will give notice via email, social media, and our website. We understand that this may affect registration deadlines and capacities in some classes, but we intend to accommodate all registrations within reason to ensure that students can participate in classes. Thank you for your continued support of Big Lake Community Education!

Just a reminder that this Thursday, Friday and upcoming Monday (April 9, 10, and 13) there is no school. As there is no school, meals will not be available for pick up or delivered to bus stops. In anticipation of this, we have prepared extra meals for students that will be available tomorrow.

Students can pick up meals at the middle school from 7:30 am - 12:30 pm or they will be delivered to identified bus stops tomorrow between 9-9:30 a.m. Please plan on bringing a bag or other container to help carry multiple meals. Bus routes may be slightly behind schedule tomorrow to accommodate the extra time needed to deliver these additional meals.

post_text:
Distance Learning F.A.Q.
What steps are Big Lake Schools taking to ensure that my child is safe while using Zoom?

Answer: Teachers have the ability to block Zoom meeting participants' cameras, disable their Zoom chat capabilities, and boot participants from meetings altogether to help keep all students safe. Teachers treat student behavior within Zoom meetings the same way as a physical classroom setting, and will report any student misconduct to parents and administrators.

Zoom has enabled a "Waiting Room" feature where teachers will have the ability to admit students individually into the virtual classroom before class begins. This empowers teachers to have more control over their virtual classrooms.

If you have any questions or feedback on distance learning we encourage you to fill out our parent feedback form. We will utilize any submissions on this form to coordinate communication with our families so that you are not overwhelmed. You can access the form here: https://bit.ly/2Jl7qew

Distance Learning F.A.Q.
What are students supposed to do for elective classes like physical education, art, culinary, music, etc.?

Answer: Elective classes such as physical education, art, culinary, music, and others will follow the same format as our student's core classes like math, science, and english language arts. Each elective class has a page on the Student Portal (blstudent.org) where students are able to view their lessons and assignments. Our teachers have been coming up with creative ways to deliver these classes through a distance learning format!

If you have any questions or feedback on distance learning we encourage you to fill out our parent feedback form. We will utilize any submissions on this form to coordinate communication with our families so that you are not overwhelmed. You can access the form here: https://bit.ly/2Jl7qew

Distance Learning F.A.Q.
When will teachers post assignments or lessons for students to complete and how do I access their lessons?

Answer: Tomorrow, Monday March 30, all lessons will be posted by 9 am for students to access. Going forward, students and families will be able to access instructional and learning resources on our Student Portal (blstudent.org). It is highly recommended that you bookmark this page. Teachers are expected to post the weekly overview by Sunday evening and each day’s lessons the night before (i.e. Tuesday's lessons need to be posted by Monday evening).

If you have any questions or feedback on distance learning we encourage you to fill out our parent feedback form. We will utilize any submissions on this form to coordinate communication with our families so that you are not overwhelmed. You can access the form here: https://bit.ly/2Jl7qew

post_text:
Distance Learning F.A.Q.
My child was working with a school counselor or social worker, will this continue?

Answer: Yes! Our school counselors and social workers will continue supporting students. We recognize that students and families may need additional support during this transition to distance learning. If you feel your student needs assistance, please reach out to your student's teacher for a referral to a school counselor or social worker.

There are many community organizations that partner directly with Big Lake Schools to help support our students and families. You can find a list of resources beginning on page 15 of our Distance Learning Guide (bit.ly/BLSguide).

If you have any questions or feedback on distance learning we encourage you to fill out our parent feedback form. We will utilize any submissions on this form to coordinate communication with our families so that you are not overwhelmed. You can access the form here: https://bit.ly/2Jl7qew

post_text:
Distance Learning F.A.Q.
Are students allowed to complete their work at their own pace for the day?

Answer: Yes! We recognize that many older students will be helping watch younger siblings while their parents are at work or that younger students may be at daycare without the resources to complete distance learning. Each family dynamic is different which is why building your own schedule is fine! On page 9 of our Distance Learning Guide (bit.ly/BLSguide) we shared examples of what schedules may look like for students. If you have questions about your individual situation, please talk to your student's teacher and/or principal.

If you have any questions or feedback on distance learning we encourage you to fill out our parent feedback form. We will utilize any submissions on this form to coordinate communication with our families so that you are not overwhelmed. You can access the form here: https://bit.ly/2Jl7qew

Big Lake’s own Shark Tank! Students in Ms. Spaulding’s class pitched unique product and service ideas to local business professionals in a “Shark Tank” style format. Students were asked questions on target markets, similarity to existing products, profit margins, and return on investments.

Special thanks to our “Sharks” Paul Knier, Financial Advisor at Cabot Lodge Securities; Donna Clarksean, Banking Center Manager at Old National Bank; Russ Scheller, Operations Manager at Arconic Engineered Solutions; and Becky Jacobs, President at Northstar Technology Solutions.

Congratulations to these student musicians for representing BIg Like well at the Mankato State University Honor Band: Hailey Crowe - Horn, Jaden Anderson - Trumpet, Hannah Renslow - Flute, McKenna Peterson - Alto Sax & Joshua Hunt - Trombone

The Honor Band included 125 musicians from 28 high schools throughout Minnesota. The students participated in multiple rehearsals and attended master classes. The Honor Band culminated in a concert Friday afternoon. The Honor Band was directed by Dr. Amy Roisum Foley, Director of Bands and Professor Michael Thursby, Director of Athletic Bands and Percussion Studio.
